description.narrative:
Over the last 10 years Oxfam and partners have established Saving for Change (SfC) as an effective pro-poor Savings-Led Microfinance (SLM) product in Cambodia. In 2017 over 140,000 people directly benefited from SfC and saved up to 5.7 million USD. 40 local organizations were trained by Oxfam and were capable to provide the product. The SfC groups are simple in set-up and management: groups of people come together to pool their savings in a joint savings box. Group members save small amounts of money together regularly, often weekly, and this money not only builds their own savings (giving a safety net in times of need) but is used to make loans to other group members. These loans are typically for income-generating purposes, or paying for health and education costs. Interest or a#service charge# is paid on the loans at rates determined by the group itself. At the end of the savings cycle (which typically lasts 12 months) the members receive a #share-out# of their savings, including dividends from interest paid on loans. Most SfC group also have a #social fund# which acts as a small insurance fund; members make small weekly contributions into the fund and the group can vote to give an emergency grant to any of its members from the fund.
In addition, the SfC group enhances economic security and resilience, achieve economic and social empowerment for members and their households, and therefore is an effective tool for economic development. The SfC group serves as platforms to discuss about other community issues such as economic, agriculture, livelihood, health, education, disaster risk reduction etc.

By seeing the uniqueness of SfC model, VSO requested for collaboration with Oxfam  to provide technical assistance to VSO team to mobilize fish processor members into two SfC groups through pr-assessment, ToT to VSO and it partner team and key persons, follow up and facilitating phasing out plan.  This collaboration between Oxfam and VSO starts 01 June and ends by 30th October 2018.  This collaboration is expected to deliver as five key results:
# Result I: Key challenges and possibility of forming SfC within CFis will be assessed and confirmed on their current situation and strategy to deal with key challenges will be formulated and ready work in the next step;
# Result 2:  At least 15 participants (2 VSO PAs, I VSO PO, 2 FIAC officersand 10 key persons from CFIs) will be equipped SfC ToT on how to form SfC groups including delivering 7 weekly training to groups;
# Result 3: At least 2 SfC groups with 30 members formed or transformed within CFis with proper training;
# Result 4: 2 VSO PAs, and10 key persons from CFIs) will be refreshed trained on how to provide technical support to the groups and all groups will be strengthened on group operation including bookkeeping, group internal rules, share-out formula;
# Result 5: An exit plan will be consultedwith the two SfC members key persons and group management committee to ensure the long-run of their SfC group; the final report on the project progress will be submitted to VSO.
